    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Piling On Punishment</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Stephen F Franks letter scores correctional officers who subject prisoners to shameful and humiliating attention to increase their feelings of guilt (April 7)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>When correctional officials subject prisoners to shameful and humiliating attention to increase their feelings of guilt, it only demeans us as a civilized country (''When Emotion Worms Its Way Into Law,'' Arts &amp; Ideas pages, April 7).</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>When correctional officials subject prisoners to shameful and humiliating attention to increase their feelings of guilt, it only demeans us as a civilized country (''When Emotion Worms Its Way Into Law,'' Arts &amp; Ideas pages, April 7).</p>
        <p>The negative effect of orange jumpsuits, leg irons and other devices intended to publicize prisoners' status is that prisoners further harden their attitudes toward society. They become more embittered and are more likely to strike out against society when released.</p>
        <p>If instead prisoners are not coddled but are treated decently while in confinement, they will be more likely to treat others decently when they are returned to society.</p>
        <p>STEPHEN F. FRANKS  Hendersonville, N.C., April 8, 2001</p>
        <p>The writer is a retired district court judge.</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
